headline_main: Analysis of the Nov. 20 Democratic Debate

abstract: A top envoy’s testimony places Secretary of State Mike Pompeo at the center of the nation’s biggest foreign policy controversy in nearly two decades.
snippet: A top envoy’s testimony places Secretary of State Mike Pompeo at the center of the nation’s biggest foreign policy controversy in nearly two decades.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Secretary of State Mike Pompeo has for months deflected questions about whether the Trump administration demanded political favors from Ukraine in exchange for military aid. He has refused to explain why he recalled the American ambassador, declared that it was “inappropriate” for his diplomats to testify before Congress and declined to hand over documents to impeachment investigators.

abstract: It was a mostly bloodless evening among the 10 candidates onstage, but there were some standout moments.
snippet: It was a mostly bloodless evening among the 10 candidates onstage, but there were some standout moments.
lead_paragraph: With polls showing a highly competitive primary race and no clear front-runner, the Democrats in Wednesday’s debate acted as if they had decided ahead of time to avoid taking risks or doing much of anything that might cause them to lose momentum at this stage of the campaign.

abstract: Gov. Andrew Cuomo called for an outside monitor after a series of racist incidents that has left Syracuse University besieged.
snippet: Gov. Andrew Cuomo called for an outside monitor after a series of racist incidents that has left Syracuse University besieged.
lead_paragraph: SYRACUSE, N.Y. — It was an ordinary cram session, around midnight, when the screed appeared on students’ phones. A racist manifesto, sent to a small clutch of people sitting at a Syracuse University library on Tuesday morning, warned of “the great replacement,” a right-wing conspiracy theory that predicts white genocide at the hands of minority groups.

abstract: An undercover investigation on Long Island found that real estate agents treated people of color unequally 40 percent of the time.
snippet: An undercover investigation on Long Island found that real estate agents treated people of color unequally 40 percent of the time.
lead_paragraph: One Long Island real estate agent told a black man that houses in a predominantly white neighborhood were too expensive for his budget. But the same agent showed houses in the same neighborhood to a white man with the same amount of money to spend.
